<br>
I have to admit as an Englishman the history lesson made me smile some. You see over here we are taught that the French invented the machine gun. Admittedly we weren't far behind, but I've never heard it claimed as an American invention before!<br>
<br>
Similarly the Germans used poison gas well before the Yanks entered the war. I think we did too. Firebombings I have to say I am unsure about. The famous firestorm bombing was a joint Allied operation, but that's as good as my history goes on it.<br>
<br>
Finally nukes. There's no doubt the Americans invented this right? Well actually, the reason you guys got the first nuke is because you yanked most of the German scientists. There is good evidence that they were working quite seriously on this but couldn't get the raw materials through to start testing. So if you like, German scientists invented it, American industrial muscle built it.<br>
<br>
As for sword designs, the description of the 3 fencing styles is accurate other than to say that the sabre is the most aggressive style rather than epee. Liq is correct in stating that the saber was primarily a mounted sword; it was the traditional weapon of Cuirasseurs.<br>
<br>
Also, in Middle Age Europe, noone really had the technology to make a true cutting edge that could pierce armour. The Japanese did at this time and that is why their swords are curved whilst European swords remained straight.<br>
<br>
The rapier style of weapons grew from the theory that the only real way of taking out a knight was to outmaneuver them and strike at a weak patch such as under the armpit. With the introduction of gunpowder to Europe this idea became the norm for a different reason, namely because plate armour became obsolete.<br>
<br>
Cavalry, on the other hand, remained vital to warfare throughout the 19th century (they played a pivotal role in the American Civil War for example) and so the saber remained in active service through them. Indeed I believe I am correct in saying that the Poles actually used cavalry armed with sabers during the Second World War!!!<br>
<br>
So the classification of that weapon is impossible from a picture. You would have to see it and work out it's primary attack mode. If it is a light, curved, sharp cutting sword it is a scimitar. If it is a thrusting weapon, even with a slight curve, it is part of the rapier family. If it is a heavy slashing weapon then it would be considered one of the saber family. I guess you might also include what we usually these days call a shortsword if the weapon operates by a mixture of fast thrusting and slashing attacks.<br>
<br>
You can label these classification differently, but sword families are based around the attack forms by which they are useful. And the above seem to be the general possibilities for the weapon in question.<br>
<br>
My final word. I agree with the poster above me that said they thought all of the epics look wonderful. This is the first expansion for some time that I have genuinely had something to look forward with. Now if they can just improve the variety in the mob AI for the one after that...<br>
<br>
(-:   Zel   :-)<br>
