<br>
They had a similar set-up as the gatling with one difference, it had a square or round clip and when it was triggered all the bullets in the clip were fired instantly on a small spread which was seriously dangerous to people closely packed together.<br>
<br>
The clip in this case was to be manually replaced and as such it fired fairly slowly but a later version could rotate clips in place to keep firing but was considered useless as the Prussians by this time had kicked the French around a bit.<br>
An example I found punched out 30 bullets in a spread of about 2 meters roughly and took about 1 minute to replace the clip, the rotating mechanism was busted but as far as the people who showed it to me said it should have been possible to rotate a clip in place 5 times in a row taking about 10 seconds each.<br>
In the best case projection we are talking 180 bullets in about a minute which was not bad for the late 19th century.<br>
<br>
Of course doing that would more then likely blow up the gun as it would overheat, jam because of dirt in the barrels or get stuck partially in the breach, quality of the metal work and the mechanism was, hum.... rather deplorable.<br>
Surprisingly enough people prefered to forget about it and use something less likely to blow yourself up. <p>Xandria, Bard of 59 songs and proud officer of Guardians of Blood, at your service.<br>
